<h3>2 · The consensus is (a)/(b), not (c)</h3>
<p>
  Switching a theme swaps token <strong>values</strong>, never component <em>behavior</em>, in every system
  except Radix. MD3 says so explicitly; Fluent v9's static Griffel compilation enforces it; Carbon's theme is
  color-only by definition. Motion and density are usually <strong>orthogonal axes, not theme members</strong>
  — Carbon makes them separate packages, MD3 makes motion a system-wide scheme, Fluent keeps density out of
  the theme entirely. <strong>Radix is the lone bundler of behavior — and only <em>visual</em> behavior</strong>
  (radius = shape, scaling = density, panelBackground = surface treatment); even Radix never switches
  interaction logic, state machine, or focus order. There is <strong>zero prior art</strong> for bundling
  interaction behavior into a switchable theme. A consistent tiering appears everywhere
  (<strong>reference/global → semantic/alias → component</strong>); the semantic tier is universally "the
  layer a theme overrides," and behavior, where present, attaches to the <em>component</em> layer (Radix props,
  Fluent <code>size</code>, MD3 state machines), not the token layer.
</p>

<h3>3 · The token-interchange standards cap the bundle at named values</h3>
<p>
  The <strong>official DTCG Format Module has no <code>$themes</code> / theming construct</strong> — a token is
  exclusively a named value + metadata. The <code>$themes</code>/<code>$metadata</code> multi-theme convention
  is a <a href="https://docs.tokens.studio/manage-themes/themes-overview">Tokens Studio</a> vendor extension,
  <em>not</em> DTCG (confirmed by <a href="https://github.com/tokens-studio/sd-transforms">sd-transforms</a>).
  Style Dictionary models multi-theme as a <em>build-config emergent</em> (config matrices + filters +
  <code>themeable</code> transforms), never a behavioral mechanism. So a unit that must be DTCG-expressible
  (forward-adapter / portability reach) <strong>cannot carry behavioral defaults — those must live in a
  WE-owned sidecar that <em>references</em> the token bundle</strong>.
</p>

<h3>4 · This is already WE's architecture</h3>
<p>
  WE <em>is</em> the "tokens in the standard format + defaults in a WE-owned sidecar" shape the prior art
  points to. <code>webtheme</code> owns primitive + component tokens as DTCG&nbsp;2025.10 with an
  <code>extends</code> deep-merge over a platform default (<code>webtheme/tokens.ts</code>); the intents own
  the semantic tier — <em>"a token never re-coins a role name"</em>; <code>extends</code>-over-platform-default
  is the established config machinery (<code>plugs/core/CustomRegistry.ts</code>); catalogs auto-render from a
  registry (the <a href="/protocols/">/protocols/</a> + <a href="/intents/">/intents/</a> precedent); and
  traits already separate presentational from behavioral activation knobs. A WE design-system manifest that
  <em>references</em> a DTCG token doc keeps tokens portable and intent/trait defaults in the WE layer.
</p>

<h2>What it means for the forks</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Content determines entity — decide content first.</strong> Value-only bundles behave like config
    (Carbon, Style Dictionary, DTCG = flavors); bundles carrying semantic + behavioral identity behave like
    first-class entities (Fluent factory, Radix component). Flavor-vs-entity <em>follows</em> the
    tokens-only-vs-tokens+behavior call.</li>
  <li><strong>A new fork the original framing missed: the <em>scope</em> of trait defaults.</strong> Visual
    behavior (radius/density/motion-feel) has one precedent (Radix); interaction behavior has none. The
    novelty/risk concentrates here, so it deserves its own fork.</li>
  <li><strong>The DTCG ceiling validates the sidecar shape</strong> — manifest references DTCG tokens, doesn't
    embed them.</li>
  <li><strong>A switchable gallery still needs a registry to render from</strong> (catalog-auto-render rule),
    so the bundle being "just a manifest" and a <code>/design-systems/</code> catalog surface resolve together.</li>
</ul>

